<TITLE> More diarrhoea patients flock to hospital </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Aug 12 (bdnews24.com)  Dhaka's cholera hospital Monday treated a further 500 diarrhoea patients as the waterborne disease rampaged through parts of the country in the wake of receding floodwaters, according to a midday count. As many as 1,000 patients are treated at ICDDR,B every day as diarrhoea cases stretched the limit of the hospital. Of the 500 new diarrhoea cases, 20 serious patients were sent to the Combined Military Hospital in Dhaka. Dr Shahadat Hossain, a physician at ICDDR,B, told bdnews24.com: "The situation is under control." Army chief Moeen U Ahmed Sunday said some patients from ICDDR,B would be sent to CMH to ease pressure on the specialised hospital. He also said that if necessary doctors from CMH would come to ICDDR,B to help doctors there. More to follow bdnews
